<F P=100> Central Eurasia </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Diplomatic Sources' Say Li Peng To Visit Central Asia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2403103694 Tokyo KYODO in English 1011 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2403103694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 24 KYODO -- Chinese Premier Li Peng 
will visit four former Soviet states in Central Asia in April, 
diplomatic sources in Beijing said Thursday [24 March]. 
  The premier will visit Uzbekistan, Turkmenistan, Kyrgyzstan 
and Kazakhstan from April 18 to 28, a diplomatic source said. 
  The visit will be the first visit by a top Chinese leader to 
a country belonging to the Commonwealth of Independent States 
since the breakup of the Soviet Union in 1991. 
  A visit by President Jiang Zemin to Russia could happen in 
the fall, the source said. 
  The high-level visits are seen as resulting from China's 
determination to engage in economic and trade activities with 
its neighbors, especially in light of recent frictions in 
Sino-U.S. relations, analysts said. 
  The trip will be the first overseas visit for Li since going 
to Vietnam in November 1992. Li's trip, which originally 
included a trip to Mongolia, was first scheduled for April last 
year, but was canceled after he had a heart attack. 
  Mongolia is presently consulting with China for a visit by 
Li 
in June or July, the source said. 
  Trade, especially in oil and oil exploration, will be the 
main theme of the trip, the diplomat said, with a 90-member 
Chinese ministerial and business delegation expected to 
accompany Li. 
  A border agreement with Kazakhstan will also be signed, he 
said. 

</TEXT>

