<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK Envoy Views Benefits of Kim Yong-sam's Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2403084494 Beijing XINHUA in English 0816 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2403084494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing March 24 (XINHUA) -- The upcoming visit to 
China by President Kim Young-sam of the Republic of Korea (ROK), 
will further promote the two countries' relations, especially in 
the economic field, said the ROK's ambassador to China, Hwang 
Pyong-tae, in a recent interview here with XINHUA. 
  Hwang noted that although it is only a year and a half since 
the two countries set up diplomatic ties, China and ROK have 
greatly increased political, economic and cultural contacts. 
  He said that the trade volume between the two countries last 
year reached 9.1 billion U.S. dollars, an increase of 50 percent 
over 1992. 
  He noted that China has become ROK's third largest trade 
partner and ROK is now the sixth largest trade partner of China, 
adding that by the end of last year ROK's total investment in 
China exceeded one billion U.S. dollars. 
  Hwang predicted that the annual trade volume between China 
and ROK will increase greatly by the year 2000 if the two sides 
keep up the current momentum of economic and trade cooperation. 
  Exchanges in the cultural and other fields between the two 
countries are increasing as well, the ambassador said, adding 
some of the well-known universities, such as Beijing University 
and Fudan University (in Shanghai), now have research institutes 
on ROK studies. 
  More than 150,000 people from the ROK toured China last 
year, 
according to Hwang, and is estimated to grow to about 500,000 
this year. 
  On the prospect of Sino-ROK ties in the 21st century, Hwang 
said that the biggest problem of the coming century would be the 
economy. He stressed that China and ROK, bringing their 
respective economic advantages into play, should make joint 
efforts to strengthen their economic cooperation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

