<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhou Nan: More Political Parties To Cause `Instability' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK2203090694 Hong Kong HONGKONG STANDARD in English 22 Mar 
94 p 3 </F>

<F P=103> HK2203090694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong HONGKONG STANDARD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Shiny Li in Beijing] </F>
  [Excerpt] A senior Chinese official has warned that an 
increase in the number of new political parties in Hong Kong 
would cause instability in the territory. 
  In a candid reference to the growing number of political 
groups, director of the Xinhua News Agency in Hong Kong, Zhou 
Nan, said: "If three or four persons are able to form a 
political party, the number of parties would be more than the 
rebellions in the Cultural Revolution. 
  "Then it will be difficult to maintain stability -- and Hong 
Kong cannot be without stability." 
  Mr Zhou also said he would like a meeting with Governor 
Chris 
Patten one day -- to discuss poetry, not politics. 
  Mr Zhou was speaking at a poetry meeting he initiated for 
reporters in Beijing. 
  He said too many political parties meant too many choices 
for 
Hong Kong people. 
  China, he stressed, could never fully adopt the Western 
style 
of parliament. 
  "China has her own style for democratic development," he 
said. "We should not and need not take the Western style for 
reference because China is a democratic country and we have got 
wider democracy." 
  Recalling conversations with members of Britain's House of 
Lords, Mr Zhou said: "If Britain has taken about 400 years to 
develop this style of Parliament, how can Hong Kong take only a 
few years to come up to that point?" Mr Zhou also said the 
greatest wish of China's paramount leader Deng Xiaoping was to 
stand on Hong Kong soil, even if only for a minute, after it was 
returned to China in 1997. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

