<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sino-UK Row To Affect Cross-Border Road Upgrade Plans </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK2203085994 Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST in English 
22 Mar 94 p 6 </F>

<F P=103> HK2203085994 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Linda Choy] </F>
  [Text] Plans to upgrade cross-border road links between 
China and Hong Kong would be hit by the Sino-British political 
row, the head of the Ministry of Communications, Huang Zhenlai, 
said yesterday. 
  Mr Huang, who was attending the National People's Congress 
meeting, said there was "nothing to discuss" with Britain which 
was adopting an "unco-operative" attitude with China over 
political development in Hong Kong. 
  His comment, different in tone to Chinese Foreign Minister 
Qian Qichen, cast doubt on projects to ease traffic congestion 
between China and Hong Kong. 
  Mr Qian had pledged that China was willing to cooperate with 
Britain on issues outside politics. 
  The Shenzhen government has been discussing with Hong Kong 
the 24-hour opening of the Lok Ma Chau checkpoint. 
  But Mr Huang said that although there were a few projects in 
the pipeline, discussions would not be started at present, 
apparently referring to the construction of a Shenzhen-Hong Kong 
highway. 

</TEXT>

