<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Member of Preliminary Working Committee Resigns </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK1703073594 Hong Kong HONGKONG STANDARD in English 17 Mar 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> HK1703073594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong HONGKONG STANDARD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Shiny Lin in Beijing] </F>
  [Text] Maverick Hong Kong lawyer Liu Yiu-chu has become 
the first to quit Beijing's handpicked elite preparing for the 
1997 change of sovereignty. Ms Liu's resignation yesterday from 
the Preliminary Working Committee (PWC) came as no surprise. 
She has long been an outspoken critic of the body, which 
oversees preparations for the transition. 
  In recent weeks, she had vocally criticised the nomination 
of 
pro-British Hong Kong personalities to the PWC. 
  Ms Liu had already threatened to resign on several 
occasions, 
at one time openly crying when forced to be seated next to a 
pro-British appointee during a meeting. Her resignation was 
accepted during an hour-long meeting with China's most senior 
official dealing with the territory, the director of the Hong 
Kong and Macao Affairs Office, Lu Ping. 
  "As a delegate to the NPC (National People's Congress), I 
have the responsibility to watch the work of the PWC and to give 
advice to the PWC," Ms Liu stated after her meeting with Mr Lu. 
"I think that's enough for me. In order to work better in the 
NPC, I want to resign as a member of the PWC." 
  Mr Lu will now formally report Ms Liu's resignation to the 
NPC Standing Committee. 
  When granted Mr Lu's approval to resign, it felt "just like 
a 
stone lifting up from my heart," Ms Liu said. But she warned 
that the Chinese government should not ignore the results of the 
1994-95 elections, the last ones under British rule. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

