<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   STAR TV Refuses Comment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK1703110494 Hong Kong AFP in English 1045 GMT 17 March 94 </F>
<F P=103> HK1703110494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hong Kong, March 17 (AFP)--STAR TV, the Asian 
satellite broadcaster controlled by media baron Rupert Murdoch, 
refused to comment Thursday on a press report that it plans to 
drop BBC World Service Television in favor of a Chinese movie 
channel. 
  "I don't want to speculate on it," a STAR TV spokesman said 
when questioned on the report in the latest issue of the Far 
Eastern Economic Review. 
  The newsmagazine said STAR TV -- which Murdoch's News Corp. 
Ltd. acquired last year for 525 million U.S. dollars -- would 
cease relaying the BBC to China, Taiwan and Hong Kong in May in 
favor of the new movie service. The BBC would still be 
available to STAR TV viewers in other parts of Asia and in the 
Middle East, according to the report. 
  Media analysts believe Murdoch is keen to drop the BBC -- 
which enjoys editorial autonomy -- in favor of his Sky News 
channel, now seen in Europe. China strongly criticized the BBC 
last year for a critical documentary on late chairman Mao Zedong 
that was aired in Britain, although it has yet to be repeated on 
the BBC's Asian service. 

</TEXT>

