<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shenzhen Opens Bonded Market to Foreign-Funded Ventures </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2303135094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1308 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2303135094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Shenzhen, March 23 (XINHUA) -- Shenzhen, China's 
first special economic zone, has opened its bonded capital goods 
market to foreign-funded enterprises, the city's Mayor Li Youwei 
announced here today. 
  Mayor Li told a press conference that the bonded capital 
goods market will become a national market where prices are 
about five to ten percent lower than those on the world market. 
  Foreign investors in China can buy whatever imported 
products 
they need in Shenzhen instead of going abroad so as to lower 
production costs, he added. 
  The Shenzhen bonded capital goods market has 12 affiliates 
specializing in various kinds of capital goods, with a total 
transaction reaching 400 million U.S. dollars in 1993. 
  The opening of the market, he said, will help bring the role 
of the city as a coastal special economic zone and an economic 
information center into fuller play. 

</TEXT>

