<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taipei To Host APEC Seminar on Small, Medium Businesses </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1903075094 Taipei CNA in English 0705 GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1903075094 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Y. C. Tsai] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, March 19 (CNA) -- Taiwan has won the right 
to host an Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) seminar on 
trade promotion and financing of small and medium sized 
enterprises Jan. 18-21, 1995, the government reported Saturday 
[19 March]. 
  Lin Yi-fu, deputy director of the Board of Foreign Trade 
(BOFT) under the Ministry of Economic Affairs, said that nearly 
60 delegates from the 17 APEC members, including Mainland China, 
are expected to attend the meeting. 
  Discussion will focus on export-import loans, financial 
planning, and the development of small and medium sized 
businesses, Lin pointed out. 
  To prepare for the 1995 seminar, a task force comprising 
officials from the BOFT, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the 
China External Trade Development Council, and the China 
Productivity Center will be formed. Lin will head the task 
force. 
  Observers here noted that Taiwan is well qualified to host 
the meeting as its successful experience in the development of 
small and medium sized enterprises has won recognition from the 
international community. 
  Taiwan should also bid to host an APEC ministerial level 
meeting on small and medium sized businesses, the observers 
suggested. 
  The first APEC ministerial level meeting in this regard will 
be held in Tokyo early October. Economic Affairs Minister P.K. 
Chiang will represent Taiwan at the meeting. 
  Meanwhile, Wu Jong-yi, president of the private Taiwan 
Institute of Economic Research, said that he helped promote 
Taiwan's bid to host an APEC senior officials' meeting in Taipei. 
  Wu made the remark late Friday prior to his departure for 
Kuala Lumpur, where he will join 12 other delegates from the 
United States, Japan, South Korea, Singapore, Malaysia, the 
Philippines, Thailand, Australia, Canada, Indonesia, Hong Kong, 
and Mainland China at a senior officials' meeting March 19-20. 
  APEC is scheduled to hold four senior officials' meetings 
this year. The second meeting will take place in Hong Kong in 
early June and Taiwan hopes to host the third or fourth meeting, 
Wu said. 
  The Kuala Lumpur meeting will focus on the liberalization of 
global trade, he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

