<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   SEF Delegation Leaves for Beijing </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2403080294 Taipei CNA in English 0716 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2403080294 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Sofia Wu] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, March 24 (CNA) -- An eight-member Taiwan 
delegation, headed by Deputy Secretary-General Hsu Hui-you of 
the Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF), left for Beijing Thursday 
[24 March] for talks with Mainland Chinese officials on some 
technical issues arising from increasing cross-Taiwan Strait 
exchanges. 
  Hsu said prior to his departure he will meet with officials 
of the Beijing-based Association for Relations Across the Taiwan 
Strait (ARATS) on three issues -- repatriation of illegal 
mainland immigrants and hijackers as well as a solution to 
cross-strait fishing disputes. 
  The talks will begin Friday and continue through March 30. 
If necessary, Hsu said, the schedule may be extended for one or 
two days. 
  "We are hopeful the talks will be fruitful and help pave the 
way for closer bilateral cooperation in the future," Hsu noted. 
  It will be the fourth round of SEF-ARATS talks on the three 
thorny issues since the heads of the two semi-official 
intermediary organizations met in Singapore last April. The 
first three rounds were held in Beijing, Xiamen and Taipei 
during the second half of last year. 
  Hsu said although the two sides managed to reach consensus 
on 
some points in the previous rounds of talks, fundamental 
political differences still hinder the signing of a final 
agreement on the three non-political issues. 
  Nevertheless, Hsu said, the two sides reaffirmed their 
commitment to resolve the problems during a high-level meeting 
between SEF Vice Chairman Chiao Jen-ho and his ARATS counterpart 
Tang Shubei in Beijing in early February. 
  Beijing's reluctance to recognize Taiwan's jurisdiction over 
the territories now under its control has been the greatest 
obstacle to reaching an agreement on the three basically 
administrative issues, local political observers said. 
  Hsu said he believes the Chiao-Tang meeting will speed 
proceedings at the coming talks. "I also hope Beijing will show 
its sincerity so that the talks can produce concrete results," 
he added. 
  According to a joint news statement issued at the end of the 
Chiao-Tang talks, if the two sides can reach agreements on the 
three topics, Tang Shubei will visit Taipei to sign a formal 
accord. 
  Many illegal mainland immigrants have been forced to remain 
at two detention centers in northern Taiwan for long periods of 
time because of Beijing's recalcitrance. Repeated hijackings of 
mainland commercial airliners to Taiwan have also created 
problems for Taiwan. Eleven hijackings took place since last 
April. Taiwan hopes the two issues can be resolved soon. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

