<H3> <TI>   Japanese Parliamentarians Visit Legislature on Compensation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2303132794 Taipei CNA in English 1304 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2303132794 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Flor Wang] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, March 23 (CNA) -- An eight-member 
delegation of Japanese parliamentarians, led by Kei Imoue of 
Japan's Social Democratic Party, visited Legislative Yuan 
President Tiu Sung-fan Wednesday [23 March]. 
  The Japanese are here to discuss Japan's reparations to 
Taiwan soldiers drafted by the Japanese Government to fight 
abroad during World War II, when Taiwan was still under the 
Japanese occupation. 
  Big differences remain between the two sides, with the 
Japanese side only willing to discuss six issues, including the 
amount of the soldiers' back salaries, their bank deposits, and 
insurance payments still due them, Liu said after the meeting. 
  Given that the Japanese Government has said it would 
compensate only 20 times the face value of the bank deposits, 
and the Taiwan side is demanding a 7,000-fold return, more 
rounds of talks will be needed to bridge the huge gap, Liu said. 

</TEXT>

