<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Housing, Medical System Reform Concern Beijing Residents </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK2403090894 Hong Kong ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE in Chinese 0618 
GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK2403090894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, 23 Mar (ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE)--According 
to the results of a sample opinion survey, Beijing residents are 
currently most concerned about the reform of the housing system 
(59 percent), and this is followed by their concern over the 
reform of the medical insurance system (56 percent) and the 
reform of the retirement pension system (36.7 percent). 
  The opinion poll was conducted by the Urban Socioeconomic 
Investigation Team of the State Statistical Bureau under the 
auspices of BEIJING QINGNIAN BAO [Beijing Youth News] between 23 
and 28 February. The pollers issued 1,001 questionnaires to 
Beijing residents and collected 997 replies. BEIJING QINGNIAN 
BAO reported the results on 10 March. 
  Commodity and service prices were also a major issue which 
concerned the residents of Beijing, and 46 percent of the 
respondents placed the issue of prices in the top position. 
  Other reform issues which concerned Beijing residents -- in 
addition to the housing, medical-care, and retirement pension 
reforms -- were the construction of the legal system (25 
percent), reform of the political structure (23 percent), 
educational reform (21 percent), reform of the labor, 
employment, and personnel system (19 percent), and reform of 
government institutions (15 percent). 
  Most people maintained that the most important criterion for 
assessing the success of the reform is that most people are 
better- off. People who hold this opinion accounted for 66.5 
percent of the respondents. On the other hand, 76.7 percent of 
the respondents maintained that the main threat to reform comes 
from corruption, and 72 percent of the respondents said that 
only if the government makes great efforts can the 
anticorruption struggle achieve solid results. 
  Among the Beijing residents who were polled, 79 percent 
believed that reform would improve their standard of living, but 
23 percent of older people, especially those above 65, feared 
that reform might lead to a decline in their living standards. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-3912 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi057_k_94017" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-057 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

